SIMPLE: print
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Print
<hw>Print</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Printed</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Printing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Abbrev. fr. <ets>imprint</ets>.
See <er>Imprint</er>, and <er>Press</er> to squeeze.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To fix or impress, as a stamp, mark, character, idea, etc., into or
upon something.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A look will <qex>print</qex> a thought that never may remove.</q>
<rj><qau>Surrey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Upon his breastplate he beholds a dint,⟦br⟧
Which in that field young Edward's sword did <qex>print</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir John Beaumont.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Perhaps some footsteps <qex>printed</qex> in the clay.</q>
<rj><qau>Roscommon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To stamp something in or upon; to make an impression
or mark upon by pressure, or as by pressure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Forth on his fiery steed betimes he rode,⟦br⟧
That scarcely <qex>prints</qex> the turf on which he trod.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> Specifically: <def>To strike off an impression or
impressions of, from type, or from stereotype, electrotype, or engraved
plates, or the like; in a wider sense, to do the typesetting, presswork,
etc., of (a book or other publication); <as>as, to <ex>print</ex> books,
newspapers, pictures; to <ex>print</ex> an edition of a
book.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To stamp or impress with colored figures or
patterns; <as>as, to <ex>print</ex> calico</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Photog.)</fld> <def>To take (a copy, a positive
picture, etc.), from a negative, a transparent drawing, or the like, by
the action of light upon a sensitized surface.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Printed goods</b></col>, <cd>textile fabrics printed in
patterns, especially cotton cloths, or calicoes.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Print</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Print
<hw>Print</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To use or practice the
art of typography; to take impressions of letters, figures, or
electrotypes, engraved plates, or the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To publish a book or an article.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From the moment he <qex>prints</qex>, he must except to hear no
more truth.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Print</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Print
<hw>Print</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Print</er>, <pos>v.</pos>,
<er>Imprint</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A mark made by
impression; a line, character, figure, or indentation, made by the
pressure of one thing on another; <as>as, the <ex>print</ex> of teeth or
nails in flesh; the <ex>print</ex> of the foot in sand or
snow.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where <qex>print</qex> of human feet was never seen.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A stamp or die for molding or impressing an
ornamental design upon an object; <as>as, a butter
<ex>print</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which receives an impression, as from a stamp
or mold; <as>as, a <ex>print</ex> of butter</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Printed letters; the impression taken from type, as
to excellence, form, size, etc.; <as>as, small <ex>print</ex>; large
<ex>print</ex>; this line is in <ex>print</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>That which is produced by printing.</def>
Specifically: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>An impression taken from anything, as
from an engraved plate.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>prints</xex> which we see
of antiquities.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Dryden.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A printed
publication, more especially a newspaper or other periodical.</def>
<au>Addison.</au> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>A printed cloth; a fabric figured by
stamping, especially calico or cotton cloth.</def> <sd>(d)</sd> <def>A
photographic copy, or positive picture, on prepared paper, as from a
negative, or from a drawing on transparent paper.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Founding)</fld> <def>A core print. See under
<er>Core</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Blue print</b></col>, <cd>a copy in white lines on a blue
ground, of a drawing, plan, tracing, etc., or a positive picture in blue
and white, from a negative, produced by photographic printing on
peculiarly prepared paper.</cd><-- also blueprint. Long used for
reproduction of architectural drawings, now also applied to an
architectural plan of any color, and thus (Fig.) a plan, or outline of a
plan of action; as, <ex>blueprint</ex> for action --> -- <col><b>In
print</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>In a printed form; issued from the
press; published</cd>. <au>Shak.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To the letter;
with accurateness.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧All this I speak <xex>in
print</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>Out of print</b></col>.
<cd>See under <er>Out</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Print works</b></col>, <cd>a
factory where cloth, as calico, is printed.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Printa-ble</ent>⟦br⟧
